---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <!-- Hero Widget ******************* -->

  <Hero>
    <Fragment slot="title"> Our Team </Fragment>
  </Hero>

  <!-- Lab Director ************************ -->

  <Features classes={{ container: 'pt-0 mt-0 -mt-40' }}>
    <Fragment slot="title">
      <span class="text-3xl font-semibold">Lab Director</span>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Yoosik Youm, Principal Investigator</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Yoosik Youm is the Underwood Distinguished Professor of Sociology at Yonsei University, South Korea, where
            he specializes in social network analysis, medical sociology, and social neuroscience. His research
            investigates the intricate relationships between social networks, brain structure and connectivity, and
            physical or psychological health outcomes across the lifespan. Professor Youm currently directs two
            longitudinal studies: the Korean Social Life, Health, and Aging Project (KSHAP) and the Korean Study of
            Adolescent Health (KSAH). KSHAP, initiated in 2011, examines sociocentric networks and biomarkers, including
            brain MRI scans, among older adults in rural Korean villages, revealing insights such as the association
            between social network positions and brain volume or connectivity. KSAH, initiated in 2021, focuses on high
            school students in Seoul, exploring how social networks emerge through the co-evolution of social
            connections and (dis)similar neural patterns. The study follows participants from their freshman year until
            graduation across several waves of data collection. Professor Youm earned his Ph.D. in Sociology at the
            University of Chicago and held faculty positions at the University of Illinois at Chicago before joining
            Yonsei University.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
  </Features>

  <!-- Research Professors ***************** -->

  <Features classes={{ container: 'pt-0 mt-0 -mt-10' }}>
    <Fragment slot="title">
      <span class="text-3xl font-semibold">Research Professors</span>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Won-Gyo Shin, Ph.D.</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Won-Gyo recently joined the SNN Lab. She earned her B.A. in Psychology from Sungkyunkwan University and her
            M.S. and Ph.D. in Cognitive Science and Brain &amp; Cognitive Sciences from Seoul National University. She
            then worked as a postdoctoral researcher at the Social Cognitive Neuroscience Lab at the University of
            Chicago and the Social Neuroscience Lab at Pusan National University. Her research explores how social and
            non-social resources are associated with human mind and behavior, utilizing behavioral, neuroimaging, and
            social network data.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Ahhyun Cho, Ph.D.</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Ahhyun Cho is a postdoctoral researcher in the Department of Sociology at Yonsei University. Her research
            interests include health inequality, immigrant adaptation, gender, social capital, and quantitative methods.
            In her doctoral dissertation, she conducted an empirical analysis using longitudinal data on multicultural
            adolescents in Korea to examine patterns of social capital at the individual and family levels and their
            relationship to health disparities. She has presented her research at domestic and international academic
            conferences, including the Korean Sociological Association, the Korean Population Association, and
            ANPOR-APCA. Her work has been published in SSCI journals such as the International Journal of Intercultural
            Relations, Cross- Cultural Research, and Applied Research in Quality of Life. She holds a BA, MA, and PhD
            from Ewha Woman’s University.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Sang Hee Lee, Ph.D.</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Sang Hee Lee is a post doctoral researcher in the Department of Sociology at Yonsei University. Previously,
            she received her B.A. in Chinese Language and Literature from Ewha Woman’s University and M.A. in
            International Studies from Seoul National University, after which she worked as a researcher specializing in
            Chinese economic policy. Recognizing the limitations of state and capital centered perspectives in
            addressing lived social realities, she returned to Ewha Womans University to pursue an integrated M.S./Ph.D.
            in Social Welfare. She is interested in the dual mechanisms of social capital and its role in both
            exacerbating inequality and enabling policy intervention, with an emphasis on welfare policy design and
            public welfare attitudes when implementing policies.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
  </Features>

  <!-- Graduate Students ************************ -->

  <Features classes={{ container: 'pt-0 mt-0 -mt-40' }}>
    <Fragment slot="title">
      <span class="text-3xl font-semibold">Graduate Students</span>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Kiho Sung</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Kiho earned his B.A. and M.A. in Sociology from Yonsei University and is currently pursuing a Ph.D. in the
            same field. His research examines how the structure of social relationships shapes health outcomes across
            the life course. He also explores the neural foundations of social behavior and the social basis of brain
            function by integrating socio-centric network analysis with neuroimaging. Recently, his work has focused on
            the intersection of social science and artificial intelligence, investigating how AI can enhance social
            research and how social data science can offer new insights to academia and society.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Gayoung Choi</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Gayoung is currently a post-master’s researcher at the SNN Lab. During her master’s studies, she employed
            causal mediation analysis and hierarchical linear modeling to investigate the relationship between social
            conditions and individual inequalities among older adults. Her recent research focuses on utilizing
            computational analysis methods to explore how social networks and knowledge influence individuals’
            self-perception and knowledge formation. Prior to joining the SNN Lab, she earned both her B.A. and M.A. in
            Sociology from Sungkyunkwan University.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
  </Features>

  <!-- Research Assistants ************************ -->

  <Features classes={{ container: 'pt-0 mt-0 -mt-40' }}>
    <Fragment slot="title">
      <span class="text-3xl font-semibold">Research Assistants</span>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Hyunsuh Cho</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Hyunsuh Cho is a third-year undergraduate student majoring in Sociology and Computer Science at Yonsei
            University. Her research interests lie in network science and computational sociology, particularly focusing
            on information diffusion, network dynamics, and computation for social good. She aims to further study
            algorithmic and cognitive mechanisms in social networks, using computational modeling and cognitive
            neuroscience.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Chaeun Kim</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Chaeun Kim is a fourth-year undergraduate researcher in Sociology at Yonsei University, majoring in
            Sociology. Her primary research interests include neuroscience and crime sociology. Specifically, she is
            interested in how post-victimization processing and acceptance of criminal experiences may relate to
            differences in neural activation patterns and variations in social network structure. Her research explores
            brain-computer interfacing and network-based approaches to crime, victimization, and neuro-social activation
            mechanisms.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Hyunseo Yoon</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>
            Hyunseo Yoon is a first-year undergraduate researcher in Sociology at Yonsei University. Her primary
            research interests lie in quantitative social analysis of social networks. She is primarily committed to
            transforming social structures into measurable and visualizable data to examine structural conditions and
            its process in shaping individual and collective outcomes. On a broader surface, she is interested in
            identifying structural sources of social problems and contributing to evidence-informed solutions.
            Currently, she is exploring multiple subfields of sociology, including social institutions, medical
            sociology, urban sociology.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Seokhwa Lee</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-m">
          <p>Description</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
  </Features>

  <!-- Lab Alumni ************************ -->

  <Features classes={{ container: 'pt-0 mt-0 -mt-40' }}>
    <Fragment slot="title">
      <span class="text-3xl font-semibold">Lab Alumni</span>
    </Fragment>
    {
      alumni.map((alum) => (
        <Fragment slot="subtitle">
          <div class="mt-2">
            <h2 class="text-m font-semibold mb-0">{alum.name}</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4 text-sm">
              <p set:html={alum.description} />
            </div>
          </div>
        </Fragment>
      ))
    }
  </Features>
</Layout>
